Actually, there is one aspect that we probably need to consider. If we want to pass the Trafodion database user id on to the HiveClient_JNI object and the Java org.trafodion.sql.HiveClient object, then we should do this for every call, not during the init() method. That would allow us to keep the object across connections. Doing so would only make sense if Trafodion and Hive share the same user id space, like some space defined by Kerberos. Thanks again for getting me to think more about this.
This change looks good to me. Thanks.

Change looks good. New tests are detailed. Thank you. Thank you also for collecting feedback from the community and finding common ground on the semantics.

My thinking is that we should remove calling SQL_EXEC_DeleteHbaseClient_JNI and this CLI method. It is not clear to me why should this be done outside of SQL engine via a CLI call. It might have been some residue left behind from the earlier versions of the code. 

If we remove this call, NATableDB should be able to use this across connections. NATableDB would be shared across connections if the same user comes into the mxosrvr. I believe NATableDB and other structures would be deallocated, if a different user comes into mxosrvr to take care of privileges.

Yes, that sounds good to me. As far as I understand, this would mean that we treat both HBaseClient_JNI and HiveClient_JNI the same and that we would keep both across JDBC connections (assuming the same user id). That could give us a small performance boost when applications use a lot of short connections.

Thanks Hans. Can you please remove the CLI too so that it is not used in
future.

Selva
